      "detail": "8th in Atlantic Division",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Toronto Maple Leafs' season ended not with a bang but a whimper - seven straight losses, a 32-36-14 record, and eighth place in the Atlantic Division. Thirty-one games behind the pace setter. This wasn't a collapse; it was a slow-motion surrender. <strong>The Leafs finished with 78 points, their playoff dreams officially extinguished as the regular season concluded.</strong> For a franchise that's spent two decades chasing October glory, April has become a season of reckoning.\n\nThe math was brutal and inevitable. A losing streak that long doesn't happen by accident - it's the sound of a roster running on fumes, a coaching staff out of answers, and a front office facing hard truths about roster construction. Sheldon Keefe's future hangs in the balance. Kyle Dubas's July decisions loom. The draft lottery awaits, and somewhere in the organization, someone needs to explain how a team with this payroll finishes 15th in playoff positioning.\n\n<strong>The real work starts now: gutting the cap structure, asking whether the core can coexist, and deciding if incremental tinkering is finished.</strong> Toronto's summer will define the next five years.",
        "updated": "Updated April 30, 2026"
      },
