      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Commanders",
        "body": "Adam Peters and the Washington Commanders just completed a draft that asked one question louder than any other: can a rookie class rebuild a franchise that finished 5-12 and third in the NFC East? The answer hinges on <strong>Sunny Styles, the cornerstone pick at seventh overall</strong>, a prospect the front office believes can anchor their rebuild for the next decade. But Styles alone doesn't fix a secondary that remains dangerously thin - the Commanders passed on defensive backs entirely in the draft despite glaring needs, betting instead that recently acquired Amik Robertson and Ahkello Witherspoon can hold the line while their young core of Mike Sainristil and Trey Amos develops. In the middle rounds, they added Antonio Williams, a receiver from Clemson in the third round, addressing a desperate need for a true WR2 alongside Terry McLaurin. The class graded middle-of-the-pack - 13th overall - a reflection of limited ammunition and no second-round pick. Peters isn't done: undrafted free agents, including at least two cornerbacks, arrive next week. <strong>Watch whether this patchwork secondary can survive an NFC East gauntlet loaded with elite receivers, or whether the Commanders' offseason moves amount to rearranging deck chairs on a sinking ship.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated April 30, 2026"
